commentBody:
@Lynn The Varsity is pretty much the same as its always been, as far as I know. I haven't been there in years. As far as it being a lot of dough... yes, but it took a relatively short amount of time to do it and was a small part of a very long day. I was using one of the smaller remix mixers, but it still put out about a thousand pounds of dough about every twelve minutes. 

I have had my own experiences with the police. I look vaguely like a lot of minorities. When I was in Tucson I could count on being stopped and questioned by cops within maybe 30 minutes every single time I walked somewhere. I've got a decent vocabulary, I stayed calm, and usually I could turn it into friendly conversation. 

Usually.

@Ron
I also posted this to your Saturday comment  

<a href="https://www.nytimes.com/shared/comment/433m90?rsrc=cshare&smid=url-share" target="_blank">https://www.nytimes.com/shared/comment/433m90?rsrc=cshare&smid=url-share</a>

@Dave K. 

If it's always referred to with "The" in front of it, then it makes sense as an answer.
Imagine being at a wedding on the dance floor and saying "Hey Stan! Do worm!"

@HeathieJ 
Glad you got it.  I get the same reaction with "tower," a word that has made several appearances.  Such is the world of crosswords.
Enjoy and have a great Sunday and week ahead.

@dutchiris 
@Lynn and @NYC Traveler

Thank you for trying to help, but alas, it was neither of these.

@Rory " “Crossest” made me cross."
It made me even crosser; in fact, of the all the solvers, I was by far the  . . .






Mizery loves Company.

@Rory 
I came to this thread just to find what I expected would be an outcry about Les Miz so I could push back. A few years ago "Les Miz" in a puzzle resulted in a huge kerfuffle comment , but not so today. I guess folks have moved on. But you are right. In the UK the show is known as Les Mis, but in the US all the publicity material used Les Miz and that is what has stuck in our language. For evidence, watch this trailer all the way to the end.

<a href="https://youtu.be/5s5ImbMCxtE?si=2F8vi4lYAD1Wkx08" target="_blank">https://youtu.be/5s5ImbMCxtE?si=2F8vi4lYAD1Wkx08</a>

@Bill 
Oh, and BTW,
Although at this point I can usually, with perseverance, solve even the most difficult puzzles--even this one, although I sure struggled--I have never yet completed a sudoku, even one graded "easy."

@Bill Since no one bit:

MINISTER AD

ENT ABS

@john ezra 

You are definitely not alone. 

The puzzles have been a bit of a refuge, but even basic things have left me flummoxed within them.

@kkseattle 

I stand corrected! Sounds pretty darn eerie to me.

Of course, there's lots of things going on right now that make Poe seem like Mr. Rogers' Neighborhood in comparison, but I'll concede to you and Mr. Ezersky that eerie fits the bill for EAP.

@Alex 
I'm guessing a reference to the character Yente in *Fiddler on the Roof*--rather niche, i'd say.
My first try was YENTL, also a Broadway show (and Barbra Streisand film).

@Barry Ancona Puzzles not pugilism please.  I didn’t like the puzzle, didn’t get the puzzle, bailed, even when our wise interpreters explained it.  It wasn’t fun: to me.  I rarely enjoy an Ezersky Sunday.

Most do.  Mr. Exzersky’s composure is fine.  He may even enjoy some of us saying this was a real mess.  

Altogether different from asking someone, say, to give two examples of what they found tough, only to be told they’re mistaken by someone else.  Make puzzles, not war.

@William Kash 
Maybe it could have been changed to ADDS, with SPORTS at the cross?

I've never once heard ADDY.

@Wake Up and Dream 
What does “omlet” mean?
New to me.

@CaptainQuahog 
Apparently an Omlet is a place to raise chickens in if you eventually want to make omelets.

<a href="https://www.omlet.us/chicken-coops" target="_blank">https://www.omlet.us/chicken-coops</a>/

@Nancy 

"Economics is my second least favorite and least absorbed subject -- right after Geography."

Why did Saul Steinberg's New Yorker cover come to my mind?

@Grant 
Even though I've been living in the Midwest for more than 25 years, I still call them hoagies. A decent hoagie is harder to find here than a decent pizza.

At least we have all the pho.

@AJ I got on someone from Trump World’s mailing list before the election and they all started My Friends, let’s do . . . Sorry but it triggers, or c’mon team keep at it.
I’m going to take a walk and bake something.
I’m being much too sensitive, know it and apologize.

@Kroobey - I agree. Clearly, several people were triggered by the completely valid entry, ADDY -- just because they didn't already know it. 

Instead of getting upset, perhaps they should use such events as learning opportunities. 

Sometimes the problem is not with the puzzle, but with the solver.

@Jessica Bloom 

The thick theme had nothing to do with the cluing of ADDY, which can be clued various ways. For one, it could refer to the first Black American Girl doll. 

You may not like it, but I don’t think the theme required that particular clue.

@MmmmHmm

It seems that bayonetta doesn’t live in NYC, either. 

It may be regional or generational.

@Doog I took 3x as long as you did, which was about 3x my usual. (Clearly my usual is your max. I humbly bow.)

I confess the last 40 minutes was spent Googling the many many proper names after flyspecking had proven fruitless. Just before searching the last one, Brando's role, I noticed I had simply misspelled the name of the Greek letter. Argggh.  

Oh well, along the way I spent quite a bit of time reading about many of the other answers I had already gotten right.

@Bill Thanks, maybe so! A different kind of fun, perhaps?

I actually don't mind the occasional disclosure of someone's time. The norm here is not to, and it would get old very quickly, but occasionally I find it interesting to see how quick some of the very long-time solvers are. 

I'm not trying to speed up at this point, like to enjoy the flowers along the way. So I don't feel competitive with Doog at all, just appreciative of a very different solving experience.

@Doog Thanks but speaking only for myself find input on the puzzle itself, which I found very tough, more useful than how quickly one solves.
Congrats on yours:  mine is well over an hour so far.  The star and the streak do make me feel good.
No Dis intended.

@Doog 

90% of this - self-selecting - group of solvers completed this Sunday slower than their average time. So you're in good company. 

<a href="https://xwstats.com/puzzles/2024-11-10" target="_blank">https://xwstats.com/puzzles/2024-11-10</a>

@Frances Rolater 
If you’re using the app - try closing the puzzle with the down arrow in the top right before you leave the NYT app. 

If you’re using a browser use a new tab or window for the lookups

@Josh
Think of it as two words.  ANTE (in the) PENULTIMATE hand. 

L

@Crevecoeur 

I don't know if you've read through the comments but a lot of people did find this one pretty difficult, especially for a Sunday. 

Best to you!

@B 

Ha!

I did not know that...   and it kinda just made my day!!

@B 

"/citing answers with grid coordinates is annoying for everyone and I avoid it... If you've made it this far, past the Wordplay column, you've already seen tons of spoilers, it would seem to me..."

What are you talking about, and how were you able to poll the entire population to determine it was annoying for everyone?

@Bruce @B

Agreed. One way I manage it on my phone, if I care enough about a comment to check the puzzle is: I have the app open and on the comments, but then I use another window to look up www.xwordinfo.com/Crossword?date=11/10/2024 for that day. Then I can just go back and forth. (Still, it's pretty annoying!) 

I have a subscription to it but I *think* that just seeing the last couple of crosswords is free.

@CalGal 

You're "just sayin'", but you probably shouldn't have.

In case you are new here, you may find that you will not have heard of every answer in a NY Times crossword.  If you think you have discovered an answer "nobody anywhere ever said" you might want to research before you make that claim so as to not cast yourself in a negative light amongst your fellow solvers.

@Jim 

I think it's generally better to read them from old to new... I have no science to back this up but I feel like the first half of comments tend to be more positive and any negatives are stated in a less mean spirited way. 

I have often wondered the same as your last sentence.

@Jim 

I get that. I've just found it interesting that the older comments are usually more reasonable And I often start there to get a better assessment, or more reasonable anyhow.

It seems I've otherwise agreed with your point.  ☺️
